<HEAD>Hugo Rips Through Eastern Caribbean; Heavy Thunderstorms in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo headed toward the Bahamas today after its
devasting 125 mph winds pummeled Puerto Rico, leaving tens of
thousands homeless.
   Hurricane warnings were in effect for the southern Bahamas, as
Hugo packed winds of up to 110 mph early today.
   The region's worst storm in a decade skirted Puerto Rico's
northern coast on Monday and moved northwest.
   Forecasters said sophisticated computer projections showed Hugo
turning toward the west _ and the U.S. mainland. They urged people
along the East Coast from Florida to Virginia to keep track of the
hurricane.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms and heavy rains drenched northern
California for a third day, threatening the grape harvest in the
region's wine country. On Monday, more than 2 inches of rain fell at
Red Bluff, while an inch and a half fell at Navion.
   A snow advisory was in effect this morning for elevations above
7,000 feet along the eastern slopes of the Sierra Nevadas of
California. Up to 6 inches of snow was possible.
   In western Nebraska, thunderstorms produced small hail and
locally heavy rain. Showers also were scattered over southern
Wyoming into northern Utah.
   Showers and thunderstorms also fell along the East Coast, from
northeastern Florida to the mid-Atlantic states. Some drizzle fell
over the Northeast.
   Record high temperatures for the date Monday were reported in
International Falls, Minn., with 83 degrees, and Miami, 95 degrees.
   The high for the nation on Monday was 99 degrees at Coolidge,
Ariz.
   Today's forecast called for widespread rain and isolated
thunderstorms from central and southern California through the
central Plateau and the central Rockies to western South Dakota; and
scattered showers and thunderstorms from Florida across the southern
and middle Atlantic coast into southern New England.
   Highs were expected in the 70s or 80s across much of the nation;
in the 60s from the Pacific Northwest across the northern Rockies
into northern North Dakota, the Great Basin and much of New England;
into the low to mid 90s across eastern and southern Texas, the
southern half of the Florida peninsula and over the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 29
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 80 degrees at Key West, Fla.,
and Phoenix.
